description: From Middle English cassen, from Old French casser, from Late Latin cassō, from Latin cassus (“empty, hollow”), and perhaps influenced by quassō (“to shake, shatter”).

verbs.description: cass (third-person singular simple present casses, present participle cassing, simple past and past participle cassed)

entries.meaning: (obsolete, transitive) To render useless or void; to annul; to reject; to send away.
examples: •1687 James II/VII of England, Scotland, France, and Ireland Declaration of Indulgence  : "(...)Do therefore, with Advice and Consent aforesaid, Cass, Annul and Discharge all Oaths whatsoever, by which any of Our Subjects are incapacitated or disabled from holding Places, or Offices in Our said Kingdom (...)"
